1. Introduction to HTML Attributes

    What are Attributes?
        Understanding the purpose and structure of HTML attributes.
        Syntax: attribute="value".

        html

        <tagname attribute="value">Content</tagname>

    Common Attributes:
        Overview of frequently used HTML attributes.

2. Global Attributes

    Class:
        Using the class attribute to apply CSS styles.

        html

    <p class="intro">This is an introductory paragraph.</p>

ID:

    Using the id attribute for unique element identification and styling.

    html

    <p id="main-paragraph">This is the main paragraph.</p>

Style:

    Inline CSS with the style attribute.

    html

    <p style="color: blue;">This is a blue paragraph.</p>

Title:

    Adding tooltips with the title attribute.

    html

    <p title="This is a tooltip.">Hover over this paragraph.</p>

Lang:

    Specifying the language of the element's content.

    html

    <p lang="en">This is an English paragraph.</p>

Data-*:

    Using custom data attributes for embedding custom data.

    html

        <div data-user-id="12345">User Information</div>

3. Attributes for Links and Media

    Href:
        Using the href attribute in anchor tags to define the link destination.

        html

    <a href="https://www.example.com">Visit Example</a>

Target:

    Specifying where to open the linked document.

    html

    <a href="https://www.example.com" target="_blank">Open in new tab</a>

Src:

    Specifying the source file for images, audio, and video.

    html

    <img src="image.jpg" alt="Description">
    <audio src="audio.mp3" controls></audio>
    <video src="video.mp4" controls></video>

Alt:

    Providing alternative text for images.

    html

        <img src="image.jpg" alt="A beautiful scenery">

4. Attributes for Forms

    Action and Method:
        Specifying the form submission URL and HTTP method.

        html

    <form action="/submit" method="post">
      <input type="text" name="username">
      <input type="submit" value="Submit">
    </form>

Name:

    Naming form elements for server-side processing.

    html

    <input type="text" name="username">

Placeholder:

    Adding placeholder text in input fields.

    html

    <input type="text" placeholder="Enter your name">

Value:

    Defining the default value of an input element.

    html

    <input type="text" value="Default Text">

Disabled and Readonly:

    Disabling form elements or making them read-only.

    html

        <input type="text" disabled>
        <input type="text" readonly>

5. Event Attributes

    Onclick:
        Handling click events.

        html

    <button onclick="alert('Button clicked!')">Click me</button>

Onchange:

    Handling changes to form elements.

    html

    <input type="text" onchange="alert('Value changed!')">

Onmouseover and Onmouseout:

    Handling mouse events.

    html

        <p onmouseover="this.style.color='red'" onmouseout="this.style.color='black'">Hover over this text.</p>

6. HTML5 Data Attributes

    Custom Data Attributes:
        Embedding custom data in HTML elements using data-*.

        html

    <div data-product-id="1234">Product Information</div>

Accessing Data Attributes with JavaScript:

    Using JavaScript to interact with data attributes.

    html

        <script>
          const product = document.querySelector('div');
          console.log(product.dataset.productId);  // Output: 1234
        </script>

7. SEO and Accessibility Attributes

    Meta Tags:
        Using meta tags for SEO and accessibility.

        html

    <meta name="description" content="A description of the webpage for SEO.">
    <meta name="keywords" content="HTML, attributes, tutorial">

Role and Aria-*:

    Enhancing accessibility with ARIA roles and properties.

    html

        <div role="banner">Banner content</div>
        <button aria-label="Close">X</button>

8. Deprecated Attributes

    Avoiding Deprecated Attributes:
        Understanding which attributes are deprecated and their modern replacements.

        html

<!-- Deprecated -->
<font color="red">Red text</font>

<!-- Modern Replacement -->
<p style="color: red;">Red text</p>
